Bank Churn Prediction¶

Author: Jinad Patel¶

Email: jinadpatel@gmail.com¶

GitHub URL: https://github.com/GreatLearningAIML1/gl-pgp-aiml-uta-intl-may20-jinadpatel/tree/master/Project6_Bank_Churn_Predictor¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not.

Context:¶

Businesses like banks which provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance etc.

Observations:¶

  • 'RowNumber': This is a numerical column and it's unique for each observations. It might not be useful to determine it's correlation with target variable.
  • 'CustomerId': This is a numerical column and unique for each observations. It might not be useful to determine the correlation with target variable.
  • 'CreditScore': From the data, min is 350 and max is 850. Mean is 650.53 and Median is 652, which is very close to each other. The distribution looks fairly normal.
  • 'Age': min age is 18 and max is 92. Mean is 38 and median is 37. Data distribution looks fairly normal and wide range of customers are there.
  • 'Tenure': min is 0 and mac is 10. Mean is 5 and median is 5. Data distribution looks fairly normal.
  • 'Balance': min is 0 and max is 250,900. Mean is 76485 and median is 97198. Also observations up to 1st quartile(25%) have 0 balance, which indicated skeweness in the data set.
  • 'NumOfProducts': Categorical column, min is 1 and max is 4. Mean is 1.53 and median is 1. Data distribution for this column looks fair.
  • 'HasCrCard': This is a categorical column and values are 0 or 1.
  • 'isActiveMember': This is categorical column and calues are 0 or 1.
  • 'EstimatedSalary': Numerical Column, min is 11.58 and max is 199,992. Mean is 100,090 and Median is 149,388. There are observations with salary of 51000 up to 1st quartile (25%), shows skewness in the data. May be outliers are present here.
  • 'Exit': This is Categorical column, this looks like a valid candidate for the target variable. This shows values of either 0 or 1 which denotes whether customer has stayed with the bank or not.

Note: 'Gender' & 'Geography' are categorical columns and they are good candidates for the one hot encoding. We will go through data processing later.

Initialize and Build model¶

  • Define the model and all the hidden layers with standard hyperparameters and see the output

Model 1 (Without any improvements):¶

In [22]:
# 1st layer (Input layer)

ins = keras.Input(shape=(11,), name="in_layer")

# 2nd layer(Hidden layer 1):  We will use leaky_relu as activation function since we have the negative values as the result of the scaled data.
x = layers.Dense(50, activation=tf.nn.leaky_relu, name='hl_1') (ins)

# 3rd layer (Hidden layer 2): We will use relu as a 3rd layer (2nd hidden layer)
x = layers.Dense(20, activation=tf.nn.relu, name='hl_2') (x)

# 4th layer (Hidden layer 3): We will use relu as a 4rd layer (3nd hidden layer)
x = layers.Dense(10, activation=tf.nn.relu, name='hl_3') (x)

# Final 4th layer (output layer): We will use signod as actication function since this is classification problem. This is simple binary problem so we won't be using softmax function here.
outs = layers.Dense(1, activation=tf.nn.sigmoid, name='out_layer') (x)

# Init the model
model = keras.Model(inputs=ins, outputs=outs, name='Predictor_Normal')

# Print the summary
model.summary()

# Using SGD as an optimizer and binary cross entropy as a loss function to compile the model before fitting it.

Observations:¶

  • As seen above, we are getting around 84% accuracy on the test data.
  • From the confusion metrix, False Positive and False Negative are pretty high. The model can be improved by manipulating the hyperparameters.
  • From the above graph, which shows validation loss and Training loss, we can see that validation loss is decreasing at first but than it increases drastically, which shows clear sign of overfitting. Also, we don't see the flat plato for the training loss with 100 epochs.
  • All these above analysis depicts that we can tune the hyperprameters and improve the model performance.

Points of improvements¶

  • Hyperparameters used here can be the good candidates to improve the model performance. Let's discuss the possible candidates to improve the model.

    • 'learning_rate': Currenly we took the learning rate as 0.001. This can be improved as clearly from above graph we were unable to reach to the local minima. We can choose the value to be 0.0001 to increase the accuracy.
    • 'Loss function': Loss function can be changed. I have used leaky_relu, relu and sigmoid. We can try tanh, and such combinations. Also, Number of neurons in each layer can also be manipulated.
    • 'Optimizers': We can use different types of optimizers such as Adam, SGD etc. and see if that improves the performance.
    • 'Batch size': Batch size can be changed, Currently, I used 50 but the number can be manipulated.
    • 'epochs': Epochs plays crucial role and the times the model adjust the weights and biases. This number also plays crucial role to calculate the accuracy.

  • Let's try different hyperparametes and comeup with final set. Note that, we can also use GridsearchCV or RandomsearchCV to find best matching parameters but due to time contraints I am going to try different parameters and demonstrate the final chosen one below to compare the results with the improved one.

Model 2 (Improved)¶

In [28]:
# Modified the number of neurons for each layer. I have chose 60,30,15 and that yields best output
# 1st layer (Input layer)

ins_1 = keras.Input(shape=(11,), name="in_layer")

# 2nd layer(Hidden layer 1):  We will use leaky_relu as activation function since we have the negative values as the result of the scaled data.
x_1 = layers.Dense(65, activation=tf.nn.leaky_relu, name='hl_1') (ins_1)

# 3rd layer (Hidden layer 2): We will use relu as a 3rd layer (2nd hidden layer)
x_1 = layers.Dense(35, activation=tf.nn.relu, name='hl_2') (x_1)

# 4th layer (Hidden layer 3): We will use tanh as a 4rd layer (3nd hidden layer)
x_1 = layers.Dense(18, activation=tf.nn.tanh, name='hl_3') (x_1)

# Final 4th layer (output layer): We will use signod as actication function since this is classification problem. This is simple binary problem so we won't be using softmax function here.
outs_1 = layers.Dense(1, activation=tf.nn.sigmoid, name='out_layer') (x_1)

# Init the model
model = keras.Model(inputs=ins_1, outputs=outs_1, name='Predictor_Improved')

# Print the summary
model.summary()

Comparison and Conclusion:¶

  • As we seen both normal without any hyperparameters tuned model and improved model with hyperparameters tuned model. We see some improvements for sure in the later one.
  • I have discussed all the hyperparameters on the top and later one shows the best possible combination to get best accuracy out of it. Also, the Taining loss and validation loss descreases.
  • The Validation loss is decreasing gradually and it leads to flat curve after 100 epochs. This demontstrates that our model is not overfit.
  • The Training loss is decreasing as well and it leads to flat curve after 100 epochs.
  • Overall Test accuracy is also increased from 84% to 86%.

  • Confusion metrics shows the improvements in the precision and recall. These evaluation metric parameters plays crucial role for the banking sector. False Positives were improved from 114 to 60. False Positives means, our model predicted the customers would exit but they end up not exiting. Precision score was improved from 64% to 76%. This shows good amount of improvement in the model performance.

  • To conclude, manipulating hyperparametrs and choosing right activation function leads to massive improvement in model preformance. Hence Proved!
